(368,	3,	'2015-06-30 15:20:14',	'2015-06-30 19:20:14',	'<h2>Charlestons diverse opportunities for entertainment, fun and learning makes it a great place to visit and to live! Heres a few ideas for the city explorer in all of us.</h2>\r\n<div class=\"content-block col-1-cb\">\r\n<h3>WV State Museum</h3>\r\nThis free-to-the-pubic museum offers an interactive look into the history, culture and treasures of West Virginia. The museum is designed as a timeline telling story of WV. A museum gift shop\r\noffers WV locally-made products.\r\n\r\nWV Division of Culture and History\r\nCapitol Complex\r\n1900 Kanawha Boulevard East\r\nCharleston WV 25305\r\nhttp://www.wvculture.org/museum/State-Museum-Index.html\r\n<h3>WV Humanities Council</h3>\r\nThe Council provides constant events and programs promoting the Mountain State and it\'s art, literature and history. It is located at the MacFarland-Hubbard House, which is listed on the\r\nNational Register of Historic Places.\r\n\r\n1310 Kanawha Blvd., E.\r\nCharleston, WV 25301\r\nhttp://www.wvhumanities.org/\r\n<h3>Malden</h3>\r\nHistoric town just east of Charleston. VIsit Booker T. Washington\'s childhood home, African Zion Baptist Church, J.Q. Dickenson Salt and many other historic buildings and sites.\r\n<h3>Governors Mansion</h3>\r\nTours of the Governor\'s Mansion begin on the front porch of the Mansion on Thursdays and Fridays. Reservations are required and are honored on a first-come, first-serve basis. Call for\r\nreservations at 304-558-4839.\r\n<h3>West Virginia State Capitol</h3>\r\nTours begin on the first floor Rotunda. Groups under 10 are welcome to join a regularly scheduled tour without reservations. Groups of more than 10 are best served with a reservation\r\nand tours of Senate/Representatives chamber require reservations. 304-558-2601\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"content-block col-2-cb\">\r\n<h3>Craik-Patton House</h3>\r\nCraik-Patton House was built about 1834 in the Greek Revival style. It is open for tours from April through October. It is listed on the National Register of Historic Places since 1970.\r\n\r\n2809 Kanawha Blvd. E.\r\nCharleston, WV 25311\r\nhttp://www.craik-patton.org/\r\n<h3>Coal Heritage Trail</h3>\r\nA driving trail that winds through over 187 rugged miles of scenic industrial heritage. You will pass through National Historic Districts and the physical remnants of the coal boom such as\r\ncoal miners\' homes, company stores, company offices and more.\r\n\r\n100 Kelly Avenue\r\nOak Hill, WV 25901\r\nwww.coalheritage.org\r\n<h3>Blenko Glass</h3>\r\nFor over 100 years, Blenko has maintained the tradition of hand making glassware in America. They offer a wide range of products which include functional glassware, art glass, mouth blown sheet glass, dalle de verre and other quality products. Tours are available.\r\n\r\n9 Bill Blenko Drive\r\nMilton, WV 25541\r\nhttp://www.blenko.com/\r\n<h3>Kanawha Blvd. Historical Markers</h3>\r\nAs you stroll along the riverbank, you will come across a series of historic markers commemorating moments in West Virginia history. These markers are part of the over 1,000\r\nmarkers throughout the state marking sites of significance.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"content-block col-3-cb\">\r\n<h4>Best Events<img class=\"alignleft wp-image-367\" src=\"http://localhost:8888/discovercharleston/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/capitol_night_-shutter-1-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"capitol_night_-shutter (1)\" width=\"210\" height=\"140\" /></h4>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h3>Battle of Scary Creek/Skirmish at Hurricane Bridge - Civil War Reenactment</h3>\r\nPart of a Civil War weekend in Hurricane, the event commemorates two engagements of the Civil War separated by a space of two years. The Battle of Scary Creek., July 17, 1861 and the\r\nBlue and Gray Skirmish at Hurricane Bridge, March 28, 1863. Also, enjoy crafts, sutler\'s row, storytelling, a night firing, parade drills, a ladies tea, a historical lantern tour and a military dance.\r\n<h3>WV Day Celebrations</h3>\r\nCelebrate West Virginia\'s birthday with a variety of activities on the grounds of the WV State Capitol.\r\n<h4>Best Time of the Year</h4>\r\nHistory is happening every day of the year and this is certainly the case for those wanting to learn more about Charleston and West Virginia\'s history.\r\n\r\n</div>',	'History Buff',	'',	'inherit',	'open',	'open',	'',	'191-revision-v1',	'',	'',	'2015-06-30 15:20:14',	'2015-06-30 19:20:14',	'',	191,	'http://localhost:8888/discovercharleston/uncategorized/191-revision-v1',	0,	'revision',	'',	0),
